DORINA ARELLANO: Who's next?

00:30:24.140 --> 00:30:25.050
Oh, right there.

00:30:29.070 --> 00:30:30.814
AUDIENCE: So I'm
a huge fan of Rage

00:30:30.814 --> 00:30:31.980
Against the Machine's music.

00:30:31.980 --> 00:30:32.790
I love metal music.

00:30:32.790 --> 00:30:34.180
I also love electronic music.

00:30:34.180 --> 00:30:37.290
And I tune in to watch the
Ultra Music Festival that's

00:30:37.290 --> 00:30:39.000
live streamed every year.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:41.220
So one of my favorite
groups, Knife Party,

00:30:41.220 --> 00:30:44.370
when they close out their
set and bring you out

00:30:44.370 --> 00:30:49.140
to this gigantic crowd to wow
them with this explosive guitar

00:30:49.140 --> 00:30:51.487
playing overlay with
dubstep and this crazy kind

00:30:51.487 --> 00:30:53.820
of electronic music, how'd
that feel for the first time?

00:30:53.820 --> 00:30:54.270
TOM MORELLO: Yeah, that was--

00:30:54.270 --> 00:30:55.728
I mean, that was
really the first--

00:30:55.728 --> 00:30:58.380
I was an enemy of EDM music.

00:30:58.380 --> 00:31:00.000
I thought it was--

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:02.400
I knew it only as
Italian taxicab music,

00:31:02.400 --> 00:31:05.890
or like Ibiza yacht awfulness.

00:31:08.460 --> 00:31:10.860
Until a metal friend turned
me on to Knife Party,

00:31:10.860 --> 00:31:13.270
who is in the EDM genre.

00:31:13.270 --> 00:31:16.220
But I felt the same aggression
and tension and release

00:31:16.220 --> 00:31:17.770
as in my favorite rock and roll.

00:31:17.770 --> 00:31:20.850
They were the first people
that I reached out to and said,

00:31:20.850 --> 00:31:21.520
I have an idea.

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:23.910
What if you do
what you do and we

00:31:23.910 --> 00:31:25.455
replace some of
your synthesizers

00:31:25.455 --> 00:31:26.790
with my electric guitar?

00:31:26.790 --> 00:31:28.290
The idea being if
my electric guitar

00:31:28.290 --> 00:31:32.580
is the Ansel Adams clear
black and white photo,

00:31:32.580 --> 00:31:35.040
I want to hear the smashed
Picasso version, something

00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:38.032
that's recognizable,
but you hear it

00:31:38.032 --> 00:31:39.240
in an entirely different way.

00:31:39.240 --> 00:31:40.740
So standing at Ultra
Festival, which

00:31:40.740 --> 00:31:45.000
is like 135,000
16-year-olds who are wasted,

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:48.100
right, [LAUGHS] wearing
nothing but glowsticks.

00:31:48.100 --> 00:31:48.850
That's what it is.

00:31:48.850 --> 00:31:50.130
It's in Miami.

00:31:50.130 --> 00:31:52.680
It's insane.

00:31:52.680 --> 00:31:56.090
Which is my usual
audience, right?

00:31:56.090 --> 00:31:58.389
So I go out on
stage to play this--

00:31:58.389 --> 00:32:00.180
it's the collaborated
song "Battle Sirens,"

00:32:00.180 --> 00:32:02.679
which is on this new record,
but we wrote it some years ago.

00:32:02.679 --> 00:32:04.720
That was like maybe
two or three years ago.

00:32:04.720 --> 00:32:06.960
And so I go out on stage
and I'm ready to rock,

00:32:06.960 --> 00:32:11.790
and then I would notice that
their crew, as an EDM crew,

00:32:11.790 --> 00:32:13.860
they've never mic'd
an amplifier before.

00:32:13.860 --> 00:32:15.420
So there's no mic on my amp.

00:32:15.420 --> 00:32:18.400
So there's like a PA system
ready to not hear me.

00:32:18.400 --> 00:32:21.000
And I'm headed towards like
another ptt moment, right?

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:23.100
So fortunately, at
the last minute,

00:32:23.100 --> 00:32:24.420
they did put a mic on it.

00:32:24.420 --> 00:32:25.795
And if you check
that on YouTube,

00:32:25.795 --> 00:32:29.192
it's a really awesome
moment in collaboration.

00:32:29.192 --> 00:32:31.650
That really made me think that
there was something in this.

00:32:31.650 --> 00:32:33.009
So thanks for being there.

00:32:33.009 --> 00:32:34.800
AUDIENCE: Thank you so
much for the answer.

00:32:34.800 --> 00:32:34.960
TOM MORELLO: Sure.

00:32:34.960 --> 00:32:35.440
Sure.

00:32:35.440 --> 00:32:35.940
Sure.

00:32:38.414 --> 00:32:40.830
AUDIENCE: I've been a big fan
of Rage Against the Machine,

00:32:40.830 --> 00:32:43.020
I would say, for a
long time as well.

00:32:43.020 --> 00:32:45.780
Seeing as you're so interested
in unusual sounds and things

00:32:45.780 --> 00:32:47.640
like that, and a lot
of rock musicians

00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:49.590
have moved in this
direction, have you ever

00:32:49.590 --> 00:32:53.079
been interested in doing film
music or television music?

00:32:53.079 --> 00:32:55.120
TOM MORELLO: I've done a
lot of film in the past.

00:32:55.120 --> 00:32:58.560
I did the rock score for
two of the "Iron Man" movies

00:32:58.560 --> 00:33:01.454
and have appeared on a number
of soundtracks and scores.

00:33:01.454 --> 00:33:02.370
One of things that I--

00:33:02.370 --> 00:33:04.810
I did a couple of Michael
Mann movies as well.

00:33:04.810 --> 00:33:08.627
And while it's a--

00:33:08.627 --> 00:33:10.460
I like it in theory
better than in practice.

00:33:10.460 --> 00:33:12.584
Because one thing when
you do music scoring,

00:33:12.584 --> 00:33:15.000
you have something that you
don't have when you're a band.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:16.440
And that is, you have a boss.

00:33:16.440 --> 00:33:19.100
Then you have someone who
wants to hear it sadder.

00:33:19.100 --> 00:33:20.870
And like, what do
you mean sadder?

00:33:20.870 --> 00:33:24.450
[LAUGHS] You have these
sort of directorial geniuses

00:33:24.450 --> 00:33:27.600
who do not have the
musical vocabulary

00:33:27.600 --> 00:33:29.365
to help to guide you.

00:33:29.365 --> 00:33:30.240
I forget what it was.

00:33:30.240 --> 00:33:32.880
I did a score for a movie
that I don't know if I ever

00:33:32.880 --> 00:33:34.088
saw it at the end of the day.

00:33:34.088 --> 00:33:35.240
But it was for "A Team."

00:33:35.240 --> 00:33:36.670
It was like the Mr. T reboot.

00:33:36.670 --> 00:33:37.170
Anyway.

00:33:37.170 --> 00:33:40.620
And so we spent so
much time on that.

00:33:40.620 --> 00:33:43.170
It needed to be cut-- it
was this 12-minute sequence

00:33:43.170 --> 00:33:45.540
and it needed to be
everything completely spot on.

00:33:45.540 --> 00:33:48.910
And they'd send me the
vaguest directions back.

00:33:48.910 --> 00:33:52.620
It needs to sound
more like it's played

00:33:52.620 --> 00:33:55.860
on an oasis in the
middle of an atoll.

00:33:55.860 --> 00:33:59.070
And I'm like, OK, we'll
get right on that, yeah.

00:33:59.070 --> 00:34:00.720
So just like turn
the bass up a little?

00:34:00.720 --> 00:34:01.678
Is that-- I don't know.

00:34:01.678 --> 00:34:03.450
[LAUGHS]

00:34:03.450 --> 00:34:06.430
So finally, we made it sound
like the atoll [INAUDIBLE]..

00:34:06.430 --> 00:34:10.409
And so the movie comes out,
and when I see the movie,

00:34:10.409 --> 00:34:13.739
they've taken this 12 and
1/2 minute musical piece that

00:34:13.739 --> 00:34:15.466
was meticulously
tailored to the film,

00:34:15.466 --> 00:34:17.632
and they just put it in an
entirely different scene.

00:34:17.632 --> 00:34:20.920
[LAUGHS] Just like intact,
just in a different scene.

00:34:20.920 --> 00:34:23.080
I'm like, I guess the
atoll music goes there.

00:34:23.080 --> 00:34:24.000
Anyway.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:27.540
I'm open to it, but
I'm not seeking it out.

