00:34:35.670 --> 00:34:37.860
AUDIENCE: So in high
school, I remember

00:34:37.860 --> 00:34:41.850
there was this year or two where
these really pivotal albums

00:34:41.850 --> 00:34:43.179
came out--

00:34:43.179 --> 00:34:46.500
"Nevermind," "Ten,"
Rage's self-titled,

00:34:46.500 --> 00:34:49.337
"Badmotorfinger," all of these.

00:34:49.337 --> 00:34:51.170
Can you talk a little
bit about how much you

00:34:51.170 --> 00:34:54.239
were trying to change music
in that era versus like--

00:34:54.239 --> 00:34:54.989
TOM MORELLO: Sure.

00:34:54.989 --> 00:34:57.990
I think that it had less to
do with trying to change music

00:34:57.990 --> 00:35:00.990
and that the music
industry had a revelation

00:35:00.990 --> 00:35:03.480
with the "Nevermind" record,
and maybe the Pearl Jam "Ten"

00:35:03.480 --> 00:35:08.740
record, that they
didn't know best what

00:35:08.740 --> 00:35:10.540
was connecting with audiences.

00:35:10.540 --> 00:35:15.280
And they stepped back from the
over A&amp;R-ing and trying to mold

00:35:15.280 --> 00:35:18.580
artists into stars and going,
we don't understand Tool

00:35:18.580 --> 00:35:20.262
or Nirvana, or Rage
or Nine Inch Nails.

00:35:20.262 --> 00:35:21.970
But whatever they're
doing is connecting,

00:35:21.970 --> 00:35:23.860
so step back from it.

00:35:23.860 --> 00:35:26.500
I was in a band before
Rage Against the Machine

00:35:26.500 --> 00:35:29.920
called Lock Up, which was kind
of like a Living Color style

00:35:29.920 --> 00:35:31.180
funk rock band.

00:35:31.180 --> 00:35:32.770
And we got a record
deal, which was--

00:35:32.770 --> 00:35:35.061
I had never met a person that
had a record deal before.

00:35:35.061 --> 00:35:37.090
And so we were
very, very excited.

00:35:37.090 --> 00:35:39.250
And we did everything that
everyone asked us to do.

00:35:39.250 --> 00:35:41.770
Like the A&amp;R person
made these suggestion.

00:35:41.770 --> 00:35:44.020
The producer dampened
down some of the weirder

00:35:44.020 --> 00:35:45.020
parts of my guitar play.

00:35:45.020 --> 00:35:46.960
I'm like, well, I
guess they know best.

00:35:46.960 --> 00:35:51.327
This band Lockup also had
probably the worst album title

00:35:51.327 --> 00:35:52.660
in the history of Western music.

00:35:52.660 --> 00:35:53.784
I'll share it with you now.

00:35:53.784 --> 00:35:58.390
The record was called "Something
Bitchin' This Way Comes."

00:35:58.390 --> 00:36:00.460
And yes, that's bitchin'
with an apostrophe.

00:36:00.460 --> 00:36:04.430
[LAUGHTER] So we weren't
off to a strong start.

00:36:04.430 --> 00:36:06.010
But that band was
summarily dropped,

00:36:06.010 --> 00:36:09.169
and all the cliches that
happen, the dickings that happen

00:36:09.169 --> 00:36:10.460
to bands happened to that band.

00:36:10.460 --> 00:36:13.430
And at 27 years old, I was done.

00:36:13.430 --> 00:36:15.370
I had my grab at
the brass ring and I

00:36:15.370 --> 00:36:19.000
had failed to be an album
maker or a rock star.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.760
So I made a vow to myself
that I'm never going to play--

00:36:21.760 --> 00:36:23.050
that's not going to happen.

00:36:23.050 --> 00:36:24.970
I'm never going to play
another note of music

00:36:24.970 --> 00:36:25.970
that I don't believe in.

00:36:25.970 --> 00:36:26.710
And that's when
I started writing

00:36:26.710 --> 00:36:29.043
the riffs for the first Rage
Against the Machine Record.

00:36:29.043 --> 00:36:32.510
And was very surprised--
like that was a band--

00:36:32.510 --> 00:36:39.700
there no radio station or record
store or club in Hollywood

00:36:39.700 --> 00:36:45.801
that was booking a neo-Marxist,
multi-ethnic, punk, rap, metal

00:36:45.801 --> 00:36:46.300
band.

00:36:46.300 --> 00:36:52.330
And we made those songs in a
complete vacuum of ambition.

00:36:52.330 --> 00:36:55.180
And we just made songs that
we loved and believed in.

00:36:55.180 --> 00:36:57.670
And then, much to
our surprise, that

00:36:57.670 --> 00:37:00.010
was what connected
with a global audience.

00:37:00.010 --> 00:37:03.956
But there's a lesson in there
that's very thinly veiled.

00:37:03.956 --> 00:37:06.580
DORINA ARELLANO: Can you please
call your next album "Something

00:37:06.580 --> 00:37:07.720
Bitchin' This Way Comes?"

00:37:07.720 --> 00:37:08.680
TOM MORELLO: Oh, geez.

00:37:08.680 --> 00:37:09.795
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:09.795 --> 00:37:10.770
It's already there.

00:37:13.284 --> 00:37:14.450
AUDIENCE: A first shout out.

00:37:14.450 --> 00:37:15.825
I'm from Chicago
suburbs as well.

00:37:15.825 --> 00:37:17.957
I saw rage at
Lollapalooza three.

00:37:17.957 --> 00:37:19.040
TOM MORELLO: Which suburb?

00:37:19.040 --> 00:37:19.980
AUDIENCE: Darien.

00:37:19.980 --> 00:37:22.250
Yeah, [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:22.250 --> 00:37:26.050
So my question is, what
is with the hippo pegasus?

00:37:26.050 --> 00:37:29.470
TOM MORELLO: Well,
the image is one

00:37:29.470 --> 00:37:33.010
that feels to me like it's
as a gravitas and a weight

00:37:33.010 --> 00:37:34.220
and a power to it.

00:37:34.220 --> 00:37:35.470
It also has a beauty to it.

00:37:35.470 --> 00:37:37.540
And it's a combination
of unexpected elements.

00:37:37.540 --> 00:37:40.000
And all those three things
I see as representing

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:41.410
the music on the record.

00:37:41.410 --> 00:37:43.210
I also have loved
hippos since I was a kid

00:37:43.210 --> 00:37:44.501
and went to the Brookfield Zoo.

00:37:44.501 --> 00:37:45.490
You know what that is.

00:37:45.490 --> 00:37:46.365
AUDIENCE: Damn right.

00:37:46.365 --> 00:37:48.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:48.160 --> 00:37:49.600
AUDIENCE: Hey, Tom.

00:37:49.600 --> 00:37:51.950
Thanks for finding the
time to be here today.

00:37:51.950 --> 00:37:52.900
TOM MORELLO: Sure.

00:37:52.900 --> 00:37:54.220
AUDIENCE: So I'm a
singer from Ukraine.

00:37:54.220 --> 00:37:55.511
I've been doing rock and metal.

00:37:55.511 --> 00:37:58.495
And I had a cover band when
we did "Killing in the Name

00:37:58.495 --> 00:38:02.980
Of," but Ukrainian audience know
English enough to ask us not

00:38:02.980 --> 00:38:04.347
to do that anymore in the pubs.

00:38:04.347 --> 00:38:07.029
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:10.550 --> 00:38:11.880
So I have two questions.

00:38:11.880 --> 00:38:13.870
Basically, we just
moved a year ago.

00:38:13.870 --> 00:38:15.850
I'm just learning
the business here.

00:38:15.850 --> 00:38:17.980
And I have a full
time job, obviously.

00:38:17.980 --> 00:38:20.727
So I have a budget
of five hours a week

00:38:20.727 --> 00:38:22.810
and I'm trying to choose
between basically getting

00:38:22.810 --> 00:38:26.935
better, the songwriting, and
building a brand on YouTube.

00:38:26.935 --> 00:38:28.420
So how would you balance that?

00:38:28.420 --> 00:38:30.130
TOM MORELLO: Well, I would
say, first of all, welcome.

00:38:30.130 --> 00:38:31.810
And one thing
that's sort of crazy

00:38:31.810 --> 00:38:34.900
is how many metal dudes
there are at Google,

00:38:34.900 --> 00:38:36.430
and women are at Google.

00:38:36.430 --> 00:38:37.900
That's pretty interest.

00:38:37.900 --> 00:38:42.010
That's was a little bit
surprising, in an awesome way.

00:38:42.010 --> 00:38:44.428
No wonder it's such
a successful company.

00:38:44.428 --> 00:38:45.874
[LAUGHS]

00:38:45.874 --> 00:38:47.290
And the first thing
I would say is

00:38:47.290 --> 00:38:52.675
that the rules of how music
is made and distributed

00:38:52.675 --> 00:38:55.240
in the world are so
radically different from when

00:38:55.240 --> 00:39:01.090
I moved to Hollywood in 1986,
that my kids' babysitter's

00:39:01.090 --> 00:39:02.257
boyfriend is a YouTube star.

00:39:02.257 --> 00:39:04.215
And I just don't have
any understanding of even

00:39:04.215 --> 00:39:04.820
what he does.

00:39:04.820 --> 00:39:08.200
I don't know-- [LAUGHS] I have
no idea what that dude does.

00:39:08.200 --> 00:39:10.410
So maybe that's the best route.

00:39:10.410 --> 00:39:13.450
But I would say, my
recommendation to you

00:39:13.450 --> 00:39:15.130
is in order to be
a-- it's very, very

00:39:15.130 --> 00:39:18.760
easy to be a success
by a certain criteria.

00:39:18.760 --> 00:39:22.930
And that is, if you play and
write music that you love

00:39:22.930 --> 00:39:25.730
and that you enjoy, whether
or not there's an audience,

00:39:25.730 --> 00:39:28.275
you will have an artistic
satisfaction that is--

00:39:28.275 --> 00:39:29.650
let me tell you,
there are people

00:39:29.650 --> 00:39:31.360
who are playing stadiums
that don't have that.

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:32.990
And they do not
sleep well at night.

00:39:32.990 --> 00:39:34.720
I know them, and that's true.

00:39:34.720 --> 00:39:37.619
But then there are people
who jam in their basements

00:39:37.619 --> 00:39:39.160
on the weekend with
friends that have

00:39:39.160 --> 00:39:43.280
a fulfillment via music that is
what music is really all about.

00:39:43.280 --> 00:39:46.320
So the path to success in
2018 I can't counsel you

00:39:46.320 --> 00:39:47.710
on because I really don't know.

00:39:47.710 --> 00:39:53.860
But the path to having fun and
a very meaningful experience

00:39:53.860 --> 00:39:57.040
with music is one I would say,
write songs that you believe in

00:39:57.040 --> 00:39:58.240
and play guitar--

00:39:58.240 --> 00:39:59.980
or play songs that
you really love

00:39:59.980 --> 00:40:02.410
and enjoy it to its fullest.

00:40:02.410 --> 00:40:05.440
AUDIENCE: Quick question-- what
was the first effects pedal

00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:08.740
or processor that got you
going with experimenting?

00:40:08.740 --> 00:40:10.960
TOM MORELLO: Yeah, yeah.

00:40:10.960 --> 00:40:13.150
I remember walking to
the Highland Park music

00:40:13.150 --> 00:40:15.940
store when I could
afford an effects pedal.

00:40:15.940 --> 00:40:18.010
And I turned on the delay
pedal and had like--

00:40:18.010 --> 00:40:19.780
I just turned every
knob all the way up.

00:40:19.780 --> 00:40:21.684
And it sounded so super freaky.

00:40:21.684 --> 00:40:23.350
I'm like, that's the
most awesome thing.

00:40:23.350 --> 00:40:24.610
That's what most
guitar players do

00:40:24.610 --> 00:40:27.040
is when you get a guitar pedal,
you think that's awesome.

00:40:27.040 --> 00:40:29.890
And then you dampen it, like
you make it more subtle.

00:40:29.890 --> 00:40:32.827
And you go for like, oh,
I want to just nuance

00:40:32.827 --> 00:40:33.910
this, that, and the other.

00:40:33.910 --> 00:40:38.110
And I never lost that feeling
of let's do the crazy thing

00:40:38.110 --> 00:40:40.510
and try to experience
that same--

00:40:40.510 --> 00:40:43.300
to make people's ears freak
out like I did when I first

00:40:43.300 --> 00:40:44.680
turned that effects pedal on.

00:40:44.680 --> 00:40:47.890
In my setup, it's a
very limited number--

00:40:47.890 --> 00:40:51.580
I've embraced limitations
with regards to the equipment.

00:40:51.580 --> 00:40:54.250
I have the same four or five
effects pedals, some of which

00:40:54.250 --> 00:40:57.340
I bought at that-- that effects
pedal may be in the running

00:40:57.340 --> 00:40:59.350
there as an alternate.

00:40:59.350 --> 00:41:05.060
But my idea was to take a very
limited amount of gear and--

00:41:05.060 --> 00:41:06.570
because I never
liked the sound--

00:41:06.570 --> 00:41:07.960
when I first got
my first check--

00:41:07.960 --> 00:41:09.320
I was working for a
United States senator.

00:41:09.320 --> 00:41:10.360
I got my first check.

00:41:10.360 --> 00:41:12.610
And I went to a guitar
shop in Hollywood.

00:41:12.610 --> 00:41:14.170
And they custom made
a guitar for me.

00:41:14.170 --> 00:41:16.360
And I didn't know anything
about which fretboards--

00:41:16.360 --> 00:41:17.560
so it was a stinker.

00:41:17.560 --> 00:41:19.670
It was like an expensive,
horrible guitar.

00:41:19.670 --> 00:41:21.086
And over the course
of some years,

00:41:21.086 --> 00:41:23.320
I replaced every bit of the
electronics and the neck.

00:41:23.320 --> 00:41:26.470
And I never got it to sound
like the sound I had in my head.

00:41:26.470 --> 00:41:29.980
And so one Lockup rehearsal,
I was fed up with it

00:41:29.980 --> 00:41:33.370
and I took this amp
that I had and I--

00:41:33.370 --> 00:41:35.086
this is as good as
I can make it sound.

00:41:35.086 --> 00:41:36.460
I am unfulfilled
with this sound.

00:41:36.460 --> 00:41:37.717
I marked the settings on it.

00:41:37.717 --> 00:41:39.550
But I'm never going to
think about it again.

00:41:39.550 --> 00:41:41.300
Because I felt so much
of my creative time

00:41:41.300 --> 00:41:43.750
was being expended
chasing a tone.

00:41:43.750 --> 00:41:45.820
And I thought, this is
just going to be my sound.

00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:47.200
And now I'm going
to write song--

00:41:47.200 --> 00:41:48.950
I'm going to create with this.

00:41:48.950 --> 00:41:51.730
The markings on that amp-- it's
the amp that I used at the show

00:41:51.730 --> 00:41:52.450
last night--

00:41:52.450 --> 00:41:54.250
they haven't changed since 1988.

00:41:54.250 --> 00:41:56.650
Every song I've ever
recorded, every song I've ever

00:41:56.650 --> 00:41:58.300
played live, is with--

00:41:58.300 --> 00:42:01.630
many of those songs-- with
that guitar that I didn't feel

00:42:01.630 --> 00:42:03.830
fulfilled with and with
those amp settings.

00:42:03.830 --> 00:42:05.320
And one more sort of lesson to
draw, Rage Against the Machine,

00:42:05.320 --> 00:42:07.510
we were practicing for
a South American tour.

00:42:07.510 --> 00:42:09.740
And we had to do
it on rental gear.

00:42:09.740 --> 00:42:11.650
And we were playing
our normal Rage songs,

00:42:11.650 --> 00:42:13.330
but on not our own gear.

00:42:13.330 --> 00:42:14.690
And it sounded bad.

00:42:14.690 --> 00:42:18.110
And so Brad, the
drummer, said to me,

00:42:18.110 --> 00:42:21.220
are we really so dependent
on our gear to sound good?

00:42:21.220 --> 00:42:23.950
And I thought, that's possible,
but it's also possible

00:42:23.950 --> 00:42:25.870
that if we had started
with this gear,

00:42:25.870 --> 00:42:27.850
we would have written
songs that sounded great

00:42:27.850 --> 00:42:29.260
with these sounds.

00:42:29.260 --> 00:42:31.492
And so I think that just
not worrying so much

00:42:31.492 --> 00:42:32.950
about what the tone
is and worrying

00:42:32.950 --> 00:42:35.320
about what your
creativity can be

00:42:35.320 --> 00:42:36.827
is what would be
my recommendation.

00:42:36.827 --> 00:42:37.910
AUDIENCE: Cool, thank you.

00:42:37.910 --> 00:42:39.076
TOM MORELLO: You're welcome.

00:42:39.076 --> 00:42:40.296
DORINA ARELLANO: One more.

00:42:40.296 --> 00:42:42.566
AUDIENCE: I think
it's back to Ukraine.

00:42:42.566 --> 00:42:46.070
DORINA ARELLANO: Oh, you may
get to ask your last question.

00:42:46.070 --> 00:42:48.080
There you go.

00:42:48.080 --> 00:42:50.025
TOM MORELLO: The
Ukrainian delegation.

00:42:52.640 --> 00:42:55.455
AUDIENCE: So I'm doing a
lot of open mics right now.

00:42:55.455 --> 00:42:56.330
So what is the next--

00:42:56.330 --> 00:42:58.430
I know it's hard for
you to remember maybe,

00:42:58.430 --> 00:43:01.294
but what is the next
level after open mics

00:43:01.294 --> 00:43:02.460
but before actual thousand--

00:43:02.460 --> 00:43:04.390
TOM MORELLO: Sure.

00:43:04.390 --> 00:43:06.140
First of all, I think
open mics are great.

00:43:06.140 --> 00:43:08.690
In the height of
Audioslave's fame,

00:43:08.690 --> 00:43:10.820
I was doing open mic nights.

00:43:10.820 --> 00:43:14.180
I made four records under the
name The Nightwatchman, which

00:43:14.180 --> 00:43:16.610
is like an acoustic folk
troubadour, political kind

00:43:16.610 --> 00:43:19.160
of Woody Guthrie,
Phil Ochs thing.

00:43:19.160 --> 00:43:22.400
And on days off, I would
go and do open mic nights.

00:43:22.400 --> 00:43:23.870
And again, in those
experiences, I

00:43:23.870 --> 00:43:27.590
found playing three songs
with a latte blender

00:43:27.590 --> 00:43:29.850
whirring in the background
was really fulfilling.

00:43:29.850 --> 00:43:31.350
It was like I was communicating.

00:43:31.350 --> 00:43:34.370
And it was playing stuff
that I felt was true.

00:43:34.370 --> 00:43:36.424
And I was fighting
for my artistic soul

00:43:36.424 --> 00:43:37.340
in these coffeehouses.

00:43:37.340 --> 00:43:38.780
So there's nothing
wrong with just

00:43:38.780 --> 00:43:40.370
playing the open mic nights.

00:43:40.370 --> 00:43:42.770
I would say, if you want to
go beyond that, a key way

00:43:42.770 --> 00:43:44.020
to get better--

00:43:44.020 --> 00:43:46.940
two ways to get better are to
play live, which you're doing,

00:43:46.940 --> 00:43:48.330
and to play with other people.

00:43:48.330 --> 00:43:50.000
That's a crucial
component is to--

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:51.920
whether they're better than you,
whether they're worse than you,

00:43:51.920 --> 00:43:53.705
just the chemistry
that you get and

00:43:53.705 --> 00:43:57.920
the collaborative experience is
one that will probably be fun

00:43:57.920 --> 00:43:59.360
and you will
certainly learn from,

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:01.880
and will improve
your own playing.

00:44:01.880 --> 00:44:03.720
DORINA ARELLANO:
Well, everyone, check

00:44:03.720 --> 00:44:05.170
out "The Atlas Underground."

00:44:05.170 --> 00:44:05.910
It is out now.

00:44:05.910 --> 00:44:07.590
Thank you so much
for being here, Tom.

00:44:07.590 --> 00:44:10.131
TOM MORELLO: Thanks very much,
